<div id="review_3934734109" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3934734109" />
    <a title="Jamie Cochran" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/85453373-jamie-cochran"><img alt="Jamie Cochran" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1623276259p2/85453373.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3934734109?book_show_action=true">Apr 16, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Jamie Cochran" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Jamie Cochran" href="/user/show/85453373-jamie-cochran">Jamie Cochran</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="did not like it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">did not like it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3934734109" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer15594190201220245838">Underwhelming. <br/>A story that could’ve been told in about 100 pages has been stretched into 400, telling the same stories over and over from the same point of view. While I understand the desire to tell Nancy/the family’s story, there is strong and clear bias. Perhaps because Brad was less vocal, but I imagine that the journalistic instinct should entice you to dig a little deeper. The story immediately begins with the implication of the husband and introduces no other suspects or theories. I unde</span>
  <span id="freeText15594190201220245838" style="display:none">Underwhelming. <br />A story that could’ve been told in about 100 pages has been stretched into 400, telling the same stories over and over from the same point of view. While I understand the desire to tell Nancy/the family’s story, there is strong and clear bias. Perhaps because Brad was less vocal, but I imagine that the journalistic instinct should entice you to dig a little deeper. The story immediately begins with the implication of the husband and introduces no other suspects or theories. I understand he was the only real suspect but maybe that’s a sign that this story isn’t suited for a novel or at least such a long one. Further, I noted a few inconsistencies in the story (another reason that perhaps being less redundant would be beneficial.) <br />Overall, don’t waste your time. As mentioned in other reviews- just read a news article (you’ll get the same content in a fraction of the time.)</span>
  <a data-text-id="15594190201220245838" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
