<span id="freeTextContainer7238590760921682427"><strong>Fairly Good</strong><br/><br/>This book was fairly good although somewhat repetitious as most true crime books tend to be. It was obviously written with a bias towards Nancy&apos;s family. I couldn&apos;t count the number of times her father was referred to by his trademark graciousness, aplomb, quiet dignity.......we got it the first dozen times. I was surprised that most of the pictures didn&apos;t show Nancy and Krista looking identical. Very strong resemblance but easy enough to tell apart. But it&apos;s worthwhile reading. </span>
  <span id="freeText7238590760921682427" style="display:none"><strong>Fairly Good</strong><br /><br />This book was fairly good although somewhat repetitious as most true crime books tend to be. It was obviously written with a bias towards Nancy's family. I couldn't count the number of times her father was referred to by his trademark graciousness, aplomb, quiet dignity.......we got it the first dozen times. I was surprised that most of the pictures didn't show Nancy and Krista looking identical. Very strong resemblance but easy enough to tell apart. But it's worthwhile reading. </span>
